    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-10-08T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-10-08T05:00:00-05:00" n="309"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d309">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/537: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland (<persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_WHR1" type="from">Wilson</persName>) to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-10-08T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 8, 1932—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 8—7:48 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>23. Your 20, October 5, 2 p.m.<note n="90" xml:id="d309fn90">Not printed.</note>
                    I have just had an exhaustive discussion with <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_BE1">Beneš</persName> in which we went into many
                    aspects of the disarmament <pb facs="0391" n="293" xml:id="pg_293"/> and Far
                    Eastern questions. In the course of the conversation when I suggested that the
                    latter situation might be further prejudiced before the Council and Assembly
                    could meet by the recognition of Manchukuo by other governments, <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_BE1">Beneš</persName> replied that he did not think
                    there was any real grounds for apprehension in this respect as the nations were
                    already obligated by the declaration of March 11 and that in his opinion the
                    very first thing the Assembly must do when it met in extraordinary session was
                    to adopt a resolution to the effect that states members of the League must not
                    recognize Manchukuo. This in <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BE1"
                        >Beneš</persName>’ opinion was the first and most essential step to take,
                    even before the detailed discussion of the <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_LERB1">Lytton</persName> report. <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_BE1">Beneš</persName> intends to see <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_HE1">Herriot</persName> in Paris toward the end of
                    next week. Will discuss the Far Eastern question in special reference to
                    European application and will inform me further of his views on his return.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_WHR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
